lk, England","England":"England","Bayham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Weyland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt.","German: variant of   Wieland  .","English: variant of   Wayland  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wieland","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Erwin, Otto, Heinz, Dieter, Dietrich, Erdmann, Florian, Franz, Fritz, Gerhard.","German: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>wīg</i> ‘war’ + <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’. This name was borne by the supernaturally skilled smith of ancient Germanic folk legend, and for this reason it may in part have been given as a nickname to blacksmiths.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): presumably an adoption of the German surname."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice de Weyland was born in 1389, in Baylham, Suffolk, England, her father, John de Weyland II, was 27 and her mother, Alice FitzRalph, was 28. She married James Andrews in 1402, in Baylham, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1421, in her hometown, at the age of 32."},"et":{"1389–1421":"1389–1421","1385–1434":"1385–1434","1406–1444":"1406–1444","1407–Male":"1407–Surnud","1410–1475":"1410–1475","1363–1389":"1363–1389","1361–1389":"1361–1389","4 October 1410":"4. oktoober 1410","1363":"1363","1385":"1385","1384":"1384","1361":"1361","Abt 1406":"umbes 1406","1402":"1402","about 1407":"umbes 1407","1434":"1434","1389":"1389","1444":"1444","1421":"1421","1410":"1410","1475":"1475","1407":"1407","1406":"1406","Baylham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Baylham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Baylham, Suffolk, England":"Baylham, Suffolk, England","England":"England","Bayham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1389–1421":"1389–1421","1385–1434":"1385–1434","1406–1444":"1406–1444","1407–Male":"1407–Kuollut","1410–1475":"1410–1475","1363–1389":"1363–1389","1361–1389":"1361–1389","4 October 1410":"4. lokakuuta 1410","1363":"1363","1385":"1385","1384":"1384","1361":"1361","Abt 1406":"noin 1406","1402":"1402","about 1407":"noin 1407","1434":"1434","1389":"1389","1444":"1444","1421":"1421","1410":"1410","1475":"1475","1407":"1407","1406":"1406","Baylham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Baylham, Suffolk, Englant